<paragraph blockId="4.[812,1420,1765,2091]" box="[850,1268,1765,1789]" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">
<heading box="[850,1268,1765,1789]" fontSize="36" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" reason="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[850,1073,1765,1789]" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">Material examined.</emphasis>
<tableCitation box="[1079,1161,1765,1789]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="5.[168,220,417,437]" captionText="Table 2. Species list of medium-sized and large land mammals detected with camera traps in eight sites along the Terminos-Centla wetlands. Conservation status according to the IUCN Red List (2014) and Mexican legislation (SEMARNAT 2010). IUCN categories: (LC) Least Concern, (DD) Data Deficient, (NT) NearThreatened,and (V) Vulnerable.NOM- 059: (Th) Threatened, (En) Endangered,and (SP) Special protection.The method by which the species registration was obtained in the study sites is indicated by a P when it was obtained through camera traps, L when it was obtained through literature, and O when it was obtained by direct observation (of living animals or organic remains from traffic accidents or found in the field).In the cases where literature was the information source,the superscript indicates the specific citation." pageId="4" pageNumber="715">Table 2</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1172,1264,1765,1789]" captionStart="Figures 2–15" captionStartId="6.[168,239,1804,1824]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-14@6.[168,1419,160,1780]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 2–15. Photographs of the medium and large–sized mammal species recorded in the Terminos- Centla wetlands, in southeastern Mexico.2. Philander opossum. 3. Didelphis sp. 4. Dasypus novemcinctus. 5. Tamandua mexicana. 6. Cyclopes didactylus. 7. Ateles geoffroyi. 8. Alouatta villosa. 9. Sylvilagus floridanus. 10. Sciurus sp. 11. Coendou mexicanus. 12. Dasyprocta punctata. 13. Cuniculus paca. 14. Herpailurus yagouaroundi; 15. Leopardus pardalis. 16. Leopardus wiedii." pageId="4" pageNumber="715">Figure 8</figureCitation>
.
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[812,1420,1765,2091]" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">
The study region is close to the area where 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[1317,1418,1799,1823]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[1317,1418,1799,1823]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gray, 1849)" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[862,1133,1832,1856]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="palliata">
<emphasis box="[862,980,1832,1856]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. palliata</emphasis>
(Gray, 1849)
</taxonomicName>
are sympatric and where the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[856,962,1866,1890]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[856,962,1866,1890]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
× 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[998,1116,1866,1890]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="palliata">
<emphasis box="[998,1116,1866,1890]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. palliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hybrid has been described (
<bibRefCitation author="Kelaita MA &amp; Cortes-Ortiz L" box="[820,1181,1899,1923]" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" pagination="223 - 234" refId="ref11955" refString="Kelaita MA, Cortes-Ortiz L (2013) Morphological variation of genetically confirmed Alouatta pigra × A. palliata hybrids from a natural hybrid zone in Tabasco, Mexico. American Journal of Physical Anthropology 150 (2): 223 - 234. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / ajpa. 22196" type="journal article" year="2013">Kelaita and Cortés-Ortíz 2013</bibRefCitation>
). We only observed entirely black howler monkeys without the long yellowish fur on the flanks that is characteristic of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Reid 2009)" baseAuthorityName="Reid" baseAuthorityYear="2009" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="palliata">
<emphasis box="[1303,1420,1966,1990]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. palliata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Reid F" box="[820,939,2000,2024]" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" refId="ref12602" refString="Reid F (2009) A field guide to the mammals of Central America and Southeast Mexico. 2 nd ed. Oxford University Press, New York, 384 pp." type="book" year="2009">Reid 2009</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. For this reason, we assigned all the howler monkey observations to 
<emphasis box="[1119,1243,2033,2057]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[1119,1239,2033,2057]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosa">A. villosa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, we acknowledge that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[1014,1118,2067,2091]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[1014,1118,2067,2091]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
x 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Reid" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[1146,1262,2067,2091]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="4" pageNumber="715" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="palliata">
<emphasis box="[1146,1262,2067,2091]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="715">A. palliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hybrids could
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[168,775,160,320]" box="[168,477,160,184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="716">be present in our study area.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[168,775,160,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="716">
The species is commonly called 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lawrence" authorityYear="1933" box="[555,643,194,218]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="5" pageNumber="716" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigra">
<emphasis box="[555,643,194,218]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="716">A. pigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but there is extensive evidence to support 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lawrence" authorityYear="1933" box="[498,588,228,252]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="5" pageNumber="716" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigra">
<emphasis box="[498,588,228,252]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="716">A. pigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the correct name (
<bibRefCitation author="Brandon-Jones D" box="[177,404,262,286]" pageId="5" pageNumber="716" pagination="41 - 43" refId="ref10305" refString="Brandon-Jones D (2006) Apparent confirmation that Alouatta villosa (Gray, 1845) is a senior synonym of A. pigra Lawrence, 1933 as the species-group name for the black howler monkey of Belize, Guatemala and Mexico. Primate Conservation 21: 41 - 43. https: // doi. org / 10.1896 / 0898 - 6207.21.1.41" type="journal article" year="2006">Brandon-Jones 2006</bibRefCitation>
). However, we used 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[628,730,262,286]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="5" pageNumber="716" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[628,730,262,286]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="716">A. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
following 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez-Pulido J &amp; Gonzalez-Ruiz N &amp; Gardner AL &amp; Arroyo-Cabrales J" box="[249,557,295,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="716" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref12511" refString="Ramirez-Pulido J, Gonzalez-Ruiz N, Gardner AL, Arroyo-Cabrales J (2014) List of Recent land mammals of Mexico. Special Publications of the Museum of Texas Tech University 63: 1 - 69." type="journal article" year="2014">Ramirez-Pulido et al. (2014)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
